§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Given a real valued function (e.g., a polynomial) how do we
    compute its root. ⦉
⦉

§ Definition ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Given $f: 𝗥 → 𝗥$, we call $f(x) = 0$ a ❬nonlinear
    equation❭ (a ❬nonlinear homogenous equation❭). ⦉

  ‖ If $x ∈ 𝗥$ with $f(x) = 0$ we call $x$ a ❬root❭ or
    ❬solution❭ of $f$. ⦉
⦉

§§ Examples ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ For a classic example, suppose $s ∈ 𝗥$ is given and
    consider the function $f: 𝗥 → 𝗥$ defined by
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ f(t) = t - \sqrt{s} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Then the solutions $r ∈ 𝗥$ for which $f(r) = 0$ are those
    points for which
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ 0 = r - \sqrt{s} ⇒ r = \sqrt{s} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ In other words, the ‹roots› of $s$. ⦉
⦉

